<h2 id="Topic-discovery-via-$k$-means.">Topic discovery via $k$-means.<a class="anchor-link" href="#Topic-discovery-via-$k$-means.">&#182;</a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Problem-Description">Problem Description<a class="anchor-link" href="#Problem-Description">&#182;</a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>In this problem you will use the $k$-means algorithm
to cluster 300 Wikipedia articles using their word count histograms for 1000 words.
The Julia file <code>wikipedia_corpus.jl</code> contains the histograms as a list of 300 
1000-vectors in variable <code>article_histograms</code>. It also provides the list of article titles
in <code>article_titles</code>, and a list of the 1000 words used to create the histograms in
dictionary.</p>
<p>The file <code>kmeans.jl</code> provides a Julia implementation of the $k$-means algorithm, including the function <code>kmeans</code> which performs the clustering. The <code>kmeans</code> function accepts a
list of vectors to cluster and the number of desired clusters, $k$. It returns the centroids
as a list of vectors, a list containing the index of each vector’s closest centroid, and a
list of the value of $J$ after each iteration of $k$-means.</p>
<p>Here is an example of running $k$-means with $k = 8$ and finding the 30th article’s
centroid.</p>

<pre><code>include("wikipedia_corpus.jl")
include("kmeans.jl")
using Kmeans
centroids, labels, j_hist = kmeans(article_histograms, 8)
centroids[labels[30]]

</code></pre>
<p>The list <code>labels</code> contains the index of each vector’s closest centroid, so if the 30th entry
in <code>labels</code> is 7, then the the 30th vector’s closest centroid is the 7th entry in <code>centroids</code>.</p>
<p>There are many ways to explore your results. For example, you could print the titles
of all articles in a cluster.</p>

<pre><code>julia&gt; article_titles[labels .==16-element Array{UTF8String,1}:
"Anemometer"
"Black ice"
"Freezing rain"
...

</code></pre>
<p>Alternatively, you could find a topic’s most common words by ordering <code>dictionary</code> by
the size of its centroid’s entries. A larger entry for a word implies it was more common
in articles from that topic.</p>

<pre><code>julia&gt; dictionary[sortperm(centroids[7],rev=true)]
1000-element Array{ASCIIString,1}:
"wind"
"ice"
"temperature"
...


</code></pre>
<p>(a)  Run $k$-means 3 times for each of $k = 2, . . . , 10$, and plot the best (minimum)
final value of $J$ in the 3 runs (vertically) for each $k$ (horizontally). Create your
plot by passing a 9-vector containing your best final value of $J$ for each $k$ to the
<code>plot_j_vs_k</code> function in <code>kmeans.jl</code>.</p>
<p>(b) Investigate your clustering results for a few values of $k$ by looking at the words
and article titles associated with each centroid. Feel free to visit Wikipedia if an
article’s content is unclear from its title. Choose what you think is your best value
of $k$ and plot the value of $J$ after each iteration using the function <code>plot_j_hist</code>
in <code>kmeans.jl</code>. Also give a short description of the topics that $k$-means discovered
along with the 3 most common words from each topic.</p>

</div>

<pre>Base.sortperm(v, [alg=&lt;algorithm&gt;,] [by=&lt;transform&gt;,] [lt=&lt;comparison&gt;,] [rev=false])

   Return a permutation vector of indices of &quot;v&quot; that puts it in
   sorted order. Specify &quot;alg&quot; to choose a particular sorting
   algorithm (see Sorting Algorithms). &quot;MergeSort&quot; is used by
   default, and since it is stable, the resulting permutation will be
   the lexicographically first one that puts the input array into
   sorted order – i.e. indices of equal elements appear in ascending
   order. If you choose a non-stable sorting algorithm such as
   &quot;QuickSort&quot;, a different permutation that puts the array into
   order may be returned. The order is specified using the same
   keywords as &quot;sort!&quot;.
